•	atom: The basic unit of matter consisting of a nucleus containing protons and neutrons, surrounded by electrons
•	element: A substance that cannot be broken down into simpler substances by chemical means
•	compound: A substance formed when two or more elements are chemically bonded together
•	molecule: A group of atoms bonded together, representing the smallest unit of a chemical compound
•	periodic table: A tabular arrangement of chemical elements organized by atomic number, electron configuration, and recurring chemical properties
•	atomic number: The number of protons in the nucleus of an atom, which determines the chemical element
•	isotope: Atoms with the same number of protons but different numbers of neutrons
•	covalent bond: A chemical bond formed by the sharing of electron pairs between atoms
•	ionic bond: A chemical bond formed through the electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions
•	hydrogen bond: A weak bond between a hydrogen atom and an electronegative atom like oxygen, nitrogen, or fluorine
•	pH scale: A logarithmic scale used to specify the acidity or basicity of an aqueous solution
•	redox reaction: A chemical reaction in which the oxidation states of atoms are changed (reduction-oxidation)
•	catalyst: A substance that increases the rate of a chemical reaction without itself being consumed
•	acid: A substance that donates hydrogen ions (H+) in a solution
•	base: A substance that accepts hydrogen ions (H+) or donates hydroxide ions (OH-) in a solution
•	titration: A technique where a solution of known concentration is used to determine the concentration of an unknown solution
•	mole: The SI unit for the amount of substance, equal to about 6.022 × 10²³ elementary entities
•	stoichiometry: The calculation of reactants and products in chemical reactions
•	enthalpy: A measure of the total energy of a thermodynamic system
•	functional group: A specific group of atoms within molecules that is responsible for the characteristic chemical reactions of those molecules

